EDIT: I had to stop using this because of how terrible it is. I had bugs that stopped me from typing permanently. Pressing one key on the keyboard would duplicate entire words, any mistyped word was just added to the dictionary automatically, and the word suggestions for misspelt words were atrocious. Like, the suggestions we're populated by things that bared no resemblance to the word I was typing. This product is so bad, I have to give up on it. Shame because I like the concept, but using it for five minutes is enough to tell you developers have no interest in realizing that idea. Minuum is a great concept but not at all well executed. I'm still using it now, but it has some issues that really, really bother me. Sliding the keyboard up and down to reveal the minimalist, single line style is great. But Minuum must have one of the worst predictive word engines I've ever seen. If you have a typo, it will consistently suggest you misspelled word to you, and the next three suggestions will also be completely wrong suggestion with typos in the a manner similar to your typo. So you need to fix it manually or scroll right through the suggestions to fix it. It's mind boggling. (For example if I type gettong, it will suggest gettong and gettibg.. which are not either of what I want.) Minuum also has a serious, serious problem with spaces. As in it is incapable of registering them. I can type out a full paragraph at times and look up to see not once space was added. Not a wrong character, like something was there instead of a space. There's just nothing. And it will happen over and over. There are other issues. There's some kind of multi-touch gesture which causes Minuum to delete whatever you were typing, so occasionally if I'm typing fast I'll notice that maybe 4 characters I just typed got chunked. Not even the whole word, ehich is super confusing, just 4-5 characters. I want to keep using it amd see where it goes because I love the single line layout, but it has issues which need to be addressed.

Minuum is a really fun keyboard. I've been using it for almost two weeks now and I really like it. Its prediction algorithms do a great job and they get better the more I type. Sometimes teaching it a new word can be tedious, and there are some words that will always be difficult for it to predict which you want (such as "of" and "or"). If you ever need to type carefully (like when entering a password), you can expand the keyboard to full-size. I normally prefer using the Dvorak keyboard, but Minuum works much better with qwerty because it's hard to predict which vowels you want when they're all right next to each other.

I came looking for a perfect swipe style keyboard, but stuck with this tap type it was so intuitive. This is by far the best keyboard I've tried, and trust me, I've tried them all. The predictability is amazing. It's what makes this tiny keyboard shine. A quick two finger swipe up will expand it into a full keyboard. Swipe right on the keyboard for a space, twice for a period. Other punctuation marks show up on the suggestion bar. Swipe left to delete a word. Swipe down to toggle between ABC or 123 choices. There are 5 different character layouts to choose from. I stick with QWERTY because I'm used to it for very fast typing. I can use this keyboard a lot without even looking at it. The prediction/suggestion bar holds more than 3 words at a time. Can quickly scroll to the side to see even more. I think the price is a little steep, but I used credit built up with Google's Opinion Rewards app.

content: I paid for and use this keyboard specifically for emulated (DOS) games on my Nexus 7 (2nd edition) where I need a keyboard that has the following features: ************ A) Small... I can configure this keyboard to take up two lines: one for the row of alphabetical letters and the second (which can't be removed) is the predictive word matches.    B) Transparent... this keyboard isn't very transparent, but it's barely transparent enough... I hope that will be configurable in the future.  C) Movable... I can move it to a position on the screen that is best for a particular game.  ****** While not perfect, this fits the bill.  For general keyboard use, I just use hacker's keyboard. ******* Suggestions:    A) Allow us to disable the predictive search matches.  I don't need it, and it takes up a whole row.  I want the keyboard as small as possible.  B) Allow us to set the transparency of the background in the custom color/theme selection.  I want more transparency.  Thanks.  If I could give this 4.5 stars, I would.  I'll change this 4 star review to a 5 if/when the above is implemented.  Right now, it's the best around for my use case, but there's room for improvement.

Occasionally you will have to type something not in your dictionary, but a quick two-thumb swipe up brings out the full keyboard and you can add words easily that way.  I won't rate 5 stars because the keyboard isn't PERFECT, there is a bit of a learning curve, but if you make it past there, you'll be messaging like a pro. I'm still trying to figure out WHY, but I wouldn't fault the keyboard. If anything, it's my device. Powering off and powering on always fixes it but rebooting does not.

replyContent: We've been held back by a delay in the release of the Moto360 in Canada and a lack of 3rd party keyboard support from Google. The only way to install our keyboard now is by using a complicated process that relies on Android SDK. We did receive our Moto360 today, though and are working on finalizing the round layout released this summer.

I can finally see and use most of the screen while typing, and the accuracy is far better than I expected it to be; well above normal on-screen QWERTY keyboards, at least for me. Additionally, the floating mode makes easy one-handed typing possible on my Nexus 5, something I've been missing on larger phones for a long time. Minuum has a decent number of settings, and it is easy to customize.  There's no doubt that this keyboard is different, and takes getting used to. Vastly different than all the other keyboards - and I collect and use many. Original and functional; like swiping when it was first introduced. Unlike Swype, it doesn't exactly use a traditional qwerty kb. Instead it takes a squished qwerty and like Swype uses algorithms to predict or suggest words.  Ultimately not as fast as swiping, but great compared to single-thumb pecking. 100% works and has tons of options including a full-size kb. Add swiping to the full-size kb option and it would be my only kb!

Unless you've been indoctrinated to think qwerty keyboard layouts are the be-all, end-all of input methods, you'll immediately love Minuum.  Qwerty layouts  are based on a legacy concept designed to slow your typing down and on mobile devices they take up far too much space on your screen.  Minuum rejects these constraints and releases you from the burden of accuracy, putting your wasted CPU cycles to use to predict intelligently what you want to type, when you want to type it.  Type sloppily, embrace inaccuracy, teach the app your style and blaze into the future of input methods.

content: I've been using Minuum for around 30 mins now, and yes, it does take a fair bit of getting used to, but now I'm almost at the speed I am when using Swype.  The first thing I noticed, which may just be a case of getting used to it, is the  location of the 'Backspace' key in mini-mode. When compared to other keyboards like Swype, Samsung, iPhone, SwiftKey etc. it really seems out of place. Now I know the whole idea of the keyboard is to give you more screen real estate, but I'm using it on a Note 2, where it isn't such an issue. So I use it in 'full' mode.  The main reason I am switching from Swype, is that recent updates have rendered it laggy and buggy. Now, the main reason I use Swype is because I've tried all of the alternatives and Swype is the only one that really gets the autocorrect and prediction right! It capitalises words, brands and such very effectively, even putting accents and punctuation in to some degree.   I'll stick with Minuum, and see if it DOES in fact get better as you use it, but I think the addition of a larger dictionary with more names, brands, places etc. would put this keyboard in front of the pack.   It's fast and extremely responsive.

And it working, so I have two languages at the same time. content: I give 5 stars for the idea and implementation of this app, even though at this point it isn't my 1st pick as a keyboard.  I love the idea of this app and it works pretty well.  I've been using it for about a month.  It definitely takes some getting used to even though I already know where the keys are.  I've definitely gotten faster and better typing.  Depending on how you type, with this keyboard you may have to perform an extra step or two or three to get the letter/number/character that you are trying to type compared to a regular keyboard.  The prediction is really good as well as the gestures.  But I hate using it for user id's, passwords with multiple types of characters, addresses, urls, etc.  Anything other than a normal word is too cumbersome to do with this keyboard.  I guess for security reasons, that type of information (besides passwords) can't be part of the prediction element of the app.  This past week I found myself refusing to reply to emails because it was just too difficult and too much of a risk that it'll predict the wrong word.  I'm more of a 'precise' typist than a prediction one.  I think this is more geared towards those that rely on prediction.

I hope in time these things would be resolved.  3) If you like using Smileys or Emoji ... the APP better allow for it because this keyboard doesn't.  4) I'm SO used to swiping that this tapping keyboard, even though it allows you to tap sloppily... actually slowed me down. *So I'm betting this keyboard will go over better with people who never got into the swipe style.*  All in all - a pretty well done app that I probably won't be using much ... for now.

content: The only thing that is keeping this keyboard on my devices is the fact that this is the first unique keyboard concept that I really like. I'm going to switch to the Minuum keyboard for just one paragraph and let's see how it performs without any edits.   USING THE MINUUM KEYBOARD  His it's switched to the Minuum keyboard and B B can see how well this is working right. Is it's is a do: 393 complete Chalmers to look at what. In are typing. H  BACK TO SWIFTKEY As you can see, typing with the Minuum keyboard is a pain. The claim that you can look at what you are typing and not the keyboard is a completely bogus idea at this point. I hope this product improves but I can't honestly say it's worth $4.
replyContent: Hi Christopher, thanks for sticking with us - on some larger devices, hardware constraints prevent our gestures from being recognized properly, so we recommend going to the settings and disabling the gestures (the gesture detection is the major source of the typing errors you experienced). And thanks for taking the time to provide feedback.

content: Doubles the remaining screen space. One row = less finger movement. 1 dimension instead of 2 allows for blind accuracy. No extra keys around = no unwanted presses. Fast, smooth, super convenient. 5/5
And it does take a bit of getting used to. So much screen space freed up. Love it.

Lots of potentials, but lack of options, support just english dictionary. But it does learn new words as you type and will gets better the more you use it. It's a new typing concept so some learning curve is needed. Be patient.  Please have options to turn off spelling or prediction in full keyboard, for username and password entry.  Typing sounds option   Btw great for samsung 's multi windows / view as it takes minimal space and for small screen too.
Very accurate and easy to use. Looking forward to future updates and improvements. Very impressed with this keyboard.
Watch out swift key

After using SwiftKey and Swype for so long, this is surprisingly refreshing.  The guesses seem to be far more accurate than with the swiping method. Takes a little getting used to, and is theoretically slower, but given how often I end up correcting SwiftKey (my current primary keyboard), it saves time in the long run
Nice but I'm going to wait for a multi language update.
Finally got the keyboard. Very innovative, but as observed, words not included in the database yet can be a challenge to type. Swipe option will kill the competition :-)
Because it's not as fast. But nvm.  I hope it gets updated with it. Would 5 star for sure.
I have been waiting for a while for this and it's great. Horrible for typing usernames and passwords.

I thought there would be a learning curve, but it works off the bat. Very accurate predictions too, I just mash fingers in the general area it gets the right word every time.  It be even better with swipe mode.
Loving the keyboard best I have used in a long time

Missing words like "application".. That's not okay. The spell check that tries to learn your words is broken.. I get its a first real release, but you had a beta for a while. I'm not saying its a bad keyboard, but I'm beyond my 15 minutes.. And I just want a refund...
replyContent: Hi Justin, sorry to hear that! Minuum certainly does contain the word "application", and we'd be curious to hear more from you via email at support@minuum.com. We'll also be happy to refund your purchase if you contact us there, thanks!

content: The most impressive part of this keyboard is how easy it is to pick up. The keys are in the exact spot you would expect and the prediction software is quite impressive.

I would like to see faster response times when sliding my finger to the right to do a space and also a vetter use of the space in the suggestion boxes (right now the fonts are too small when they could be significantly larger in the same boxes - see swiftkey suggestions for example. Anyway, great work guys! Its an awesome new approach to typing. Also, please bring support to other languages, like Romanian. Seriously, we text a lot!

I have been waiting for this keyboard to release for a long time, since it will save so much space on my screen. It would have been very useful for small screen, back when I had gs2, but with bigger screens like note 2 or tablet, I have found the normal keyboards more accurate and convenient. The predictions are quite accurate, provided that you also hit the key regions quite accurately. This is never going to be more accurate than SwiftKey or other sorts because of its inherent design limitation, which does not collect y-axis input. I have already bought the app, but sadly I won't be using it as my main keyboard until I come across a very small device.

The app isn't worth the money.  It  doesn't really make the typing experience any faster. The predictions are good but this keyboard isn't good enough when you've to punch in names,  addresses,  username and password. The keys are too small to be barely be seen and after typing eyes get really strained. On a personal test the SwiftKey is faster than this keyboard. You need to get a lot of practise to complete small text.

Loving it, at first when I saw it, i was a bit intimidated by how close the letters are together but you will find that use is actually very intuitive and with time probably much faster than any other digital keyboard. Trick is to not look at the keyboard but instead at the suggestions or the text
This keyboard is unusable on my Galaxy Rugby LTE - it lags for over 10 seconds at times.
replyContent: Hi Bill, we've fixed this issue in version 1.1.2 - let us know if this update resolves your problem! Thanks, The Minuum Team

content: I love the idea for this keyboard and I really tried to get used to it but after two days of use I just had to go back to swype. It really is difficult to get used to and I had to spend a few moments each time I typed looking at the screen to find the right areas to press. I thought this would be more natural with use but it just didn't improve. Maybe this one is just not for me.

Perhaps its me but compared to Swype I couldn't type with an degree of accuracy or speed. Don't get me wrong the software works but it just seem to feel as intuitive as swyping or just typing. Nice idea though and I like the fact that it allows you to regain some screen real-estate.
i keep looking for a keyboard that takes up the least amount of screen real estate and this one takes the cake... absolutely amazing to use... definitely worth the $4...

Been using for 5 mins and already much better on it, reckon that once I'm proper used to it it will be perfect. Word prediction is beautiful and the control you have over it is brilliant. Great app, living up to hopes and dreams so far.
Can't type www.  In web b owser is auto google any time. Everything it OK.

Downloaded onto my Galaxy Note today and am pretty impressed with its predictiveness. However when I click on the tutorial section of the app to check on something, it keeps crashing. Hopefully I won't need to use that bit much more though. Disappointing amount of symbols though. Where is the pound money symbol though?
replyContent: You'll find the pound symbol (and many other symbols) by switching to the full keyboard punctuation mode (you can switch between letters/punctuation mode by flicking down, and switch to a full keyboard by long-pressing with two fingers).

content: I enjoy trying every keyboard out there and pay a price to make typing more pleasant. After all we use it everyday if not every moment. It's an android privilege that can't be had with ios. So far my favorite is SwiftKey for its better prediction accuracy and key stroke response/accuracy. There's tons of great keyboard but overtime accuracy and how much time it saves you matters. Minuum has the potential to take typing to another level. More on-screen content and very good prediction/stroke accuracy.
I love the real estate savings
:-P and thats about it. I'm a developer for 4yrs and this is my first poor rating given.
The concept is cool but u always type slower and is it really worth the extra space for typing that takes longer, I didn't think so. Shouldn't be paid and Def not that much
It would be nice to have support for other languages and an easy way to switch between them

Great new concept however it's not easy to grasp at first. Using a space bar helps but the finger always bumps into comma and period. It will be a great tool if it was swipe. Need Swipe to be the perfect keyboard. And bottom row should not include anything other than space bar.
This keyboard is awesome. It's taking me a while to get used to, but it's still great. I would suggest enabling the space bar,  because the gestures feel awkward to use.

When I finally got the email saying it was available, I went to the Play Store right away to buy this thing. Overall, quite impressed! I'm very bad with the "swipe right to space, double swipe right for punctuation" mechanic for now, so I like the option to add the spacebar. For a keyboard designed for fast, sloppy typing without taking up much space, this thing is awesome. The word prediction is unparalleled and I feel proud that fellow Canadians designed this. The ability to use a full keyboard is nice too, but someday I'll manage to use this exactly as intended. Great work! Well worth the reasonable asking price!
give it a shot.  besides the typing concept, the extra features (punctuation, dictionary management) are *extremely* well thought out.

The word prediction is laughable compared to SwiftKey. Don't trust the demo video. It makes this keyboard look amazing. Nothing could be further from the truth. If somehow this keyboard became "stuck" and I couldn't switch to another one, I would get rid this phone and buy a new one. I've tried just about every keyboard for Android, and I've used them all for 1-2 weeks before deciding whether to keep them. Within 3 hours of using Minuum I was ready to commit suicide just to avoid typing one more word...
Needs a search/enter button for internet. I need to switch keyboards to search for something. Big inconvenience. Hope the developers do something about it.
replyContent:
Hi Yasin,

You can select the "enter" button by swiping right + up on the Minuum keyboard. Also, if you have the spacebar enabled in the Minuum settings then there will always be an enter button next to the spacebar on your keyboard.

content: It only took a few seconds to become familiar with the layout and to reteach my thumbs how to type. After a minute or two, I could type quickly with a more natural feel.  The low profile allows for much more content to be displayed and doesn't fill half of my screen with keyboard junk. Bottom line, this keyboard is smooth, natural, and very intelligently predicts what you are trying to say.

Solid beta, getting used to the keyboard functionality. The more I use it, the better it gets. Any chance of this keyboard learning my "words" from SMS similar to Swiftkey? Looking forward to the evolution of this product!
Just amazing how it gets everything right and makes the dreaded typing experience on  on_screen keyboards so fun.  And it's only beta...things are only going to get better.  Can't wait for RC.
I've been waiting to get my hands on this new keyboard. So far I'm really enjoying it.
I'm buying this just to give you some extra cash so you'll add some more languages. Other than that it's brilliant
This keyboard is slowing me down significantly. I wish I could get my money back.
replyContent:
Hi Benedikt,

We have some improvements in version 1.1.2 that may resolve some speed issues, but we're also happy to offer refund to unsatisfied users - just email us at support@minuum.com.

Best,
The Minuum Team

content: Great Canadian invention. Glad they decided to use the Canadian English to start with.   Works well but takes some getting used to.
This is the best keyboard by far, And I have used every keyboard available.???

I really want to like this keyboard, but I'm finding it difficult to use as my only keyboard. I find it especially hard to enter passwords, since I use many special characters such as $ and %, which are not easily accessible. Entering my pin to unlock my phone is also hard.
replyContent: Hi Yuewei, we've fixed some issues with pin entry, let us know if version 1.1.2 resolves your issue. Also, note that if you type a password with the full keyboard, you can still flick down to quickly switch between letters and punctuation mode. Best, The Minuum Team

content: There is a very slight learning curve, but this is where the future is going. More features then you will find on any other keyboard and it's only in BETA which means it's only going to get better!
It is so simple and yet very effective.  It does take some getting used to though

The only issue so far is sometimes after inserting a space the dictionary doesn't recognize that I'm now on a new word and joins the previous word to my new word. Especially apparent when using andropenoffice,  eg... I Ican Icantype Icantypeand Icantypeandit Icantypeanditdoes Icantypeanditdoesthis! Not a bug apparent in all apps, otherwise great so far,  thanks devs
replyContent: Hi Adam, this was a bug with certain Samsung apps, which we've fixed in version 1.1.2 - can you let us know if this update solves your problems? Thanks, The Minuum Team

content: Despite everyone's griping about language compatibility, for english users, this app is probably the most useful I've ever seen.  Lets you see more screen and helps you type just as fast if not faster than with the standard keyboard.  5 stars.
Can't believe I had to pay for the beta
People must understand that this is an app in development. Of course features will be missing. Stop complaining and actually help the developers by providing helpful feedback.
Best keyboard ever! Way better than Swiftkey!
Takes a while to get used to.. Took me a day.. But once you get a hang of it,  it's pretty brilliant!

Probably the most innovative keyboard around. Only English is available and it is quite difficult to use punctuation or smiley.. Having a low position for typing may not be that comfortable if you type with thumbs. Why isn't this beta version free?!
Very impressive idea and start. I wonder if swype could one day added into the mix?

One thing I live about this keyboard is the minimum space it takes. But that's about it. I am finding it really hard to get used to, maybe because I have big fingers. It took me nearly 5 mins to type a simple tweet cuz the gestures were so sensitive  it kept switching to numbers mode. I also agree with those who say it's too early in the game to be a paid app. I'll stick with it just to see if the updates make a difference. If not  = REFUUUNDD!!
replyContent: Hi Ray, can you let us know what kind of device you're using? We're constantly improving our gesture sensitivity, and it would help tremendously if you let us know on our support forum at support.minuum.com. Thanks!

content: I use Swype and still find it more efficient. Minuum needs an auto space feature for me to make the switch permanently, just hope the developers work on it more, good start though.
The verge showed me this ;)
Surprisingly it works
Takes getting used to but very impressive.

After using this for the last 8 hours of so I can safely state that this is my keyboard of choice for now. Regarding english vs english... No problems with the keyboard's language here in Australia :) great job!
A good keyboard but i would love to see some sort of swype feature implemented in the future.
Great for big phones like the note 2. Prediction is pretty good, but it definitely helps to have it import your dictionary. Definitely takes some getting used to though.
Would love to addition of gesture typing
Nexus 7 4.3. Had a problem entering a 4 digit pin number for Avast. After entering the first number, subsequent numbers overwrote rather than succeeded. Nice idea though and I will persevere.
replyContent:
Hi Nick,

Our number typing bug is now fixed in version 1.1.2, let us know if this works for you!

Thanks,
The Minuum Team

content: Bad: only supports English; sub-par tutorial [ideally make it interactive]; price [ridiculously pricey].  Good/Amazing: Incredibly intuitive; beautiful; remarkably intelligent; surprisingly accurate.  Summary: it looks amazing, works astonishingly well, but costs quite a bit for what you're getting. Once you get over the novelty of it, it turns out to be an incredibly polished piece of software. If you have the money spare, I'd highly recommend it.   Issues: The only 'bug' [more likely a simple oversight] I've come across is whenever I correct something via the suggestions, it auto-spaces [which becomes tedious when I correct a spelling/word error I made two sentences back]. Not a big deal, but annoying.  Side note: it appears they have fixed many of the gripes early users were having in their first patch-up release, which bodes well for future development.

The learning curve to master this keyboard is at lease a few hours of relentless texting. A few options are missing in this keyboard that's the ability to remove the enter to send button. And backspace button needs to be relocated. Also its a hassle to get to and to find the symbol that you may need. Also...it need to better motive its dictionary for word prediction. Some people doesn't want to spell the word correctly all the time.
Weird but cool. I do better not looking at it.
Never have I waited for an application this much. Just awesome. Takes a while to master it's efficiency  Prediction is better than swiftkey
Really different but I'm loving this keyboard so far!
There needs to be some sort of swipe integration in this software! It is great, I love it.  But it would be perfect, and I would use it more frequently of it had swipe built into it
It's a good beta product. It hasn't replaced SwiftKey for me yet but I can see its promise. Good job with the app. Well done.
I love the idea but I feel like it needs swipe like movements, although I understand why that would be hard.
this is brand new way to get over bulky qwerty.i was waiting this!good to see it meets expectations
I like how little room it takes up. Easy to learn how to use. Only been using it for about an hour but works great!
I hate the auto-correction. This keyboard is pretty much useless when it comes to user_name. Try typing 'username'. It's so difficult to type that, the auto correction didn't even recognize it.
Excellent keyboard only problem doesn't support other language then english (it would be nice to have french) , other than that very fun to use!

This is a fantastic idea. And pretty well executed. However, the auto complete is not really helpful when searching in Google Now or in my contacts. Because it's trying to compete a real word, not a name, until I find. I should typing the whole name. This, in the end, slows the down when writing emails or searching in Google. I know it'll learn what I type eventually, and I'll keep using it, and adjust my review accordingly.

I'm pretty annoyed with most keyboards on android, so I was ready to try something new. After reenabling the space bar I was off and running. Takes a little getting used to but I think I'll be able to get pretty fast on it. I like getting the extra screen real estate as well.

I love this keyboard. I can't type quite as fast as I can on swift key, but I don't care. I can type fast enough and I'm not even fully used to it. Don't get me wrong, this keyboard is very easy to use, but the feeling takes some getting used to. I can't get over how little room it takes up. Now typing in landscape isn't ridiculous. Overall, this keyboard types fast enough for me, and brings something to the table other than just speed. (also this keyboard looks very good.)
I would recommend this to anyone great keyboard

It's an amazing idea and looks awesome, but it's just too difficult to get to grips with (unless you had a bunch of free time).  It would be better if you could increase the size of the keyboard or maybe space letters out a bit, because you spend ages looking for them. Even texting was infuriating.   It's needs a bit of work, but it could turn out to be something special.
replyContent:
Hi Chris,

You can now properly adjust the height of the keyboard by going to the settings (we fixed this as of version 1.1.2), and you can try rotating your phone to landscape mode for more widely-spaced letters. Curious to hear if this helps!

The Minuum Team

content: A breakthrough in typing technique. Just have to get used to it.
Won't even open the settings.  :-/
replyContent:
Hi Josh,

Our version 1.1.2 update hopefully fixed this crash - can you email us at support@minuum.com if you're still experiencing this problem?

Thanks,
The Minuum Team

content: I purchased this keyboard out of curiosity with the intention to quickly check it out then get a refund. I didn't expect to like it nearly as much as I do. I did not ask for a refund and this may actually become my default keyboard (even though I am a huge fan of the kii keyboard) . Where this really shines (other than the obvious - the small size) is the amazing prediction with zero lag. The success rate for predictions showing up in the list is 100% so far.
No problems so far.
I love love love this keyboard.
Like swedish :)

Really like the keyboard, the only thing I miss is the lack of other languages. I use Korean & English regularly and now find switching back & forth between Minuum & another keyboard kinda tedious now.
Lovely simplified interface size doesn't make it difficult to type that's some real prediction strength.

This app had some promise, and I decided to go for it based on the good reviews, but frankly it's not worth it. Granted, I didn't practice a ton, but after 5-10 minutes of struggling to get words correct I decided to go back to SwiftKey. Though I'm a proficient touch typist on a keyboard and on my phone, I found that I really had to focus to remember where the keys were. Additionally, forcing my thumbs to stay on the bottom of the phone was ergonomically uncomfortable.

Not really that worth 4 bucks. You can't adjust the height of the keyboard. A bit bigger and it would work much better. The prediction works well but not as well as it should. And the full size keyboard doesn't have autocorrect. Wish I could have my 4 bucks back.
replyContent:
Hi Benjamin,

We've fixed a bug with the height adjustment feature in version 1.1.2, hope this helps. And we're always happy to refund users who aren't satisfied, just send us an email at support@minuum.com.

Best,
The Minuum Team

content: It doesn't work with Microsoft one-note

OK to use except I keep forgetting the spaces...  Grr! Am a swype user so would like to see a swype type interface? Love the concept and have followed you for a while,  Good first job guys, word prediction is spot on, keep it moving on!
Taking getting used to, but I'm starting to love it
It is truly a new way to type. It will take some getting used to buy overall it is nice :)
I've had my eye on this for awhile. So far it's bit of learning curve. But I feel once I get some more understanding I should become pretty quick.
So small, ya gotta love the screen real estate.
So far it's great.

When you are using Minuum to this the only thing to keep in mind is you have to remember to swype to make spaces and then you are golden. It's takes some time to get the hang of, but it truly does speed up typing on mobile devices.

I downloaded this morning and had it up and working really quickly. It'll take a little tuning in but I'm really impressed already. Can't see me taking long to exceed normal mobile typing speed. Especially when the word prediction is so good!
Great app for being a beta app. Keep up the good work and I'll keep trying to learn this app.
We really need Arabic
It takes a bit to get used to, if you added multi language support as SwiftKey it'd be amazing!

Currently using the keyboard loving the reclaimed screen real-estate! The system works pretty well and I'm starting to get used to it even though it's only been about a half hour. Unfortunately, for this to replace my current keyboard setup I need more languages to be supported! Spanish, Japanese, and French in particular would be awesome to use with this.

I mean,  I appreciate the idea of a minimalist keyboard, but I just don't think it's practical, especially since now my fingers are kept at the very bottom of my screen.   I'm already starting to feel the cramps.  By the way,  this was typed on Minuum
Like Hungarian.
i loved this project almost since it began. or ever since i first saw it. it looks promising. is gonna take some time to get used to it though.

Fun little keyboard. Actually very accurate for its size and format; I even tested it out writing a few paragraphs for a short story I'm writing and it impressed me. Unfortunately, it reached its limit when I tried to type a U with an umlaut. Then I tried an acute accent and I couldn't find that either, even when switching the keyboard to show the full qwerty layout. It also bothered me that when switching to the full layout it only displays caps just like the iOS keyboard but that's just personal preference. Anyway, if you don't need those characters this should be an awesome keyboard. I'll probably use it from time to time simply because it's fun but it can't replace the Google keyboard for me.
Was a beta tester but it won't install here, I keep getting the invalid package file message. Will continue to try.
replyContent:
Hi Justin,

The update to version 1.1.2 should hopefully fix this for you; you can email us at support@minuum.com if you're still having trouble.

The Minuum Team

content: Even though my first language is Spanish,  I bought this keyboard just to support the developers so they can enhance it! Definitely a very interesting alternative,  may be it's a matter of getting costume to to be speedier!

This is some odd piece of software tech. I'm still in the process of training the keyboard (and you should definitely take your time to train algorithm heavy soft keyboard like this).  So far my impression is positive - this little thing should be pretty useful once it starts getting the hang of my vocabulary, but even at its current state this is a fully useable keyboard, perhaps even better than some of the more horrible regular qwerty keyboards out there.
This is probably one of the better betas I've  ever taken part in. Surprisingly easy to use even though it looks super strange at first. Definitely download it, worth the $4.

Tried it for a little while and wasn't that impressed. Back to Google's default keyboard for me. ------ edit: Decided to give it another shot after watching the website video. This time it seems to be a little more intriguing. I'll give it a go for a week or two to see how it goes. Revising my rating to a 4.
I really like this keyboard.  It picks what I type better than full keyboards.  No problems on my S4.
Easy enough to adjust to, and surprisingly accurate. Gestures feel natural. Great new keyboard.

Well I didn't know if I'd get on with this so I downloaded it to find out! Seems odd at first but with the space bar option it's just right. May take time to get used to buy absolutely loving it so far! Will rate 5 stars when more smileys are added :)
Excellent ... Will take me a  few days of getting used to
I have had it crash in my gs4 twice in 20 min. However I realize it is still early on. incredibly worth getting used to it!
Croatian dictionary please
Had this installed for only an hour now amazing really easy to use and very accurate nice one guys!
I'm impressed! But it needs layouts like colemak (and Dvorak I suppose)
Awesome keyboard, works great!  I'm really looking forward to other languages support!

It's going to take some time to reset my muscle memory from a regular sized keyboard to this but I'm stoked.  Just after practicing for a few minutes, I'm already fairly comfortable.  The real challenge will be when I have to do it without focusing! :)   Great work!

While there is promise here, it is in need of better word detection. The current state of this feature is lacking and is a huge pain when words aren't even close to being detected.  Once simple example:  My spelling isn't perfect but it isn't awful either. One would figure attempting to type the word "disappointing" would be a sinch with the built in spell check features. After 6 tries, I looked up the correct spelling and it still tool 6 times to get minuum to correctly display my intention.  In comparison, the stock Jelly Bean swipe keyboard was able to handle this task without incident.  For the money I spent on this, I was expecting this keyboard to perform a lot better. Or at least as well as a stock keyboard. Noting that this is a "beta" app, I will hold my final judgement until it is made public.
It's fast and in the ball, it's amazing how you know where the letters are and over time you will get faster and faster
I'm liking this keyboard but obviously it will take some getting use to. They should offer a free trial for people since it is a little pricey.
Getting used typing on this keyboard extremely run and new way to type
Keyboard looks way too small on HTC One in portrait. Needs vibrate in tap. Needs a flat theme. The glossy button look is played out.
The only issue I'm having is about a 1 or 2 mm gap between the keyboard and the bottom of my screen. This was not an issue in the 1.0 beta.
Glad to see this project finally take off. So far everything works perfect. Excellent work.
Takes a while to get used to it but I think once I am I will type much faster. The word prediction is better than swift key.

...this thing is sick. I'm quadlingual, so this isn't really my cup of tea YET, but just for english, it's awesome. Slowly learning and will definitely try this out more often. If I type another language on it in qwerty-mode, it'll probably fill my vocabulary with foreign words, so it'd be nice to have a fast way to switch keyboards. Haven't checked yet if there is. If not, I'll just put one in the notification bar.
Worthy app.. bit of a learning curve. .. lots of potential wish it had flow.

Wasn't too sure how much I would like this but. It really is quite special. I've been waiting for a while to get it and now I have I so far love it.  I bet it doesn't take long to be faster than typing on a "normal"  keyboard. Sony xperia z
I need to get used to this and the keyboard full space bar needs to be a bit more responsive
Worth the buy.
Typing this comment with Minuum keyboard
Just missing azerty keyboard and other languages but I'm sure we'll get that in the future and otherwise it's just perfect!
Love it so far
Let's give it a shot!
Yay it's here thanks guys
